A detailed assessment of plate rigidity can be obtained by examining the full velocity field of each plate and plotting the magnitude of the velocities against the shortest distance to the Euler pole37. Fig. 4 presents plots of the velocities sampled in the plate interiors at five times, prior to and including the reorganization event. The vast majority of the interior points follow the linear trends predicted by their inversion for the implied Euler vector. However, some points fall off the line representing rigid rotation, particularly those associated with regions where higher strain-rates are detected. All points within each detected plate interior are included in the Euler vector calculations, however, some high velocity difference (and high deformity) regions not conforming to rigid motion may be better categorized as falling within a diffuse boundary (see Fig. S5). Fig. S6 plots timeseries for the fraction of Plate A,B, and C’s surface area, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
