Observation of the accumulation of heat in parcels enveloping subducting slabs and its potential for impacting plate velocities has been identified previously. In plane-layer geometry systems featuring static plate boundaries but dynamically determined plate velocities, episodic plate reversals were described in two-dimensional geometry calculations41 and plate reorganization events were observed in three-dimensional systems23,39. As described here, in these earlier studies the impact of the buoyancy of the hot parcels was identified as a source of resistance to the ongoing downwelling flow and plate motion responsible for forming the parcels. In addition, the role of internal heating was proposed as critical to the reorganization process. However, plane-layer geometry systems become much hotter than spherical shell analogues, potentially amplifying the temperature anomalies adjacent to the downwellings in the former case42. Moreover, it could be argued that by continually drawing heat entrained by plate motion to a stationary location, the modelling of fixed plate boundaries leads to temperatures building to improbable magnitudes relative to what might be expected when plate boundary movement is possible. Nevertheless, the findings described here show that mantle driven plate reorganization events, produced by instabilities associated with buoyancy accumulation adjacent to subducting slabs, persist in spherical geometry convection and when dynamic plate boundary motion is present. Although determining a full understanding of the relationship is beyond the scope of this study, we note that slab-adjacent heat buildup and the onset of plate reorganization may be affected by plate boundary migration rate with low mobility settings possibly being associated with greater instability.Fig. 5
