A major reorganization event is recorded in continental geology and seafloor fabric during the mid-Cretaceous, at \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sim$$\end{document}105-100 Ma13,20. The event is manifested in Antarctica-South America, India-Australia and India-Antarctica fracture zone relative motions that recorded sharp changes in seafloor spreading directions following the initiation of subduction along southern continental Eurasia45. Perhaps, most relevant to the model evolution described in this study is that this change is temporally coincident with a three-fold reduction in Australia’s motion associated with cessation of long-occurring East Gondwana subduction13. The full global nature of the event is recorded in synchronous reorientation of Pacific hot-spot tracks at \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sim$$\end{document}95 Ma46.

The bend in the Hawaii-Emperor seamount chain, dated at \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sim$$\end{document}47 Ma15,18, is widely cited as the mark of a major event in the Pacific that initiated approximately 50 Ma19,20,47. This reorganization was one aspect of a wider global plate motion change that impacted the Australian47, South American48,49, Caribbean50 and Indian plates51,52. The Pacific plate’s change in absolute motion was likely a result of evolving north-west Pacific subduction settings along its modern western boundaries, including the Tonga-Kermadec arc15, the Izu-Bonin-Marianas Trench16,53,54 and Aleutian and Kuril-Kamchatka Trenches55. For example, early Eocene collision of the Olutorsky arc and Tokoro arc with Asia resulted in subduction termination, that was subsequently reinstated with a polarity reversal55 while subduction beneath the Kronotsky arc ceased during the Eocene, (transferring the arc to the Pacific Plate and setting the conditions necessary for its Miocene collision with Kamchatka55). The cessation of established intraoceanic subduction55 and onset of slab pull acting on the Pacific plate following the inception of subduction of its western periphery along the East-Asia margin is the primary candidate for the main tectonic driving force that instigated the plate’s change in motion56.

Mantle convection is modelled in a spherical shell geometry using the finite volume code STAGYY57. The grid resolution of each half of the yin-yang grid is \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$96\times 768\times 256$$\end{document}, giving an approximate 40 km dimensional azimuthal resolution for a 2900 km deep mantle. Thermal convection is modelled by solving the non-dimensional governing equations for an infinite Prandtl number Boussinesq fluid. Heating is derived from an isothermal bottom boundary (with non-dimensional temperature of 1.0) and uniform internal heating of non-dimensional value 30. The surface condition is also isothermal (with a non-dimensional temperature of zero) and both boundaries are free-slip. Upper and lower thermal boundary layers are established by the high convective vigour of the model, which is determined by specifying a Rayleigh number (Ra) of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$10^9$$\end{document}, corresponding to a reference viscosity of non-dimensional value 1.0. Mantle rheology is determined by a combined temperature-dependent and depth-dependent viscosity featuring viscoplastic yielding. The model analyzed here is the case described by Langemeyer et al.29 with a constant valued yield stress of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$2 \times 10^7$$\end{document} (110 MPa). The temperature dependence of the Arrhenius-like viscosity specified results in a viscosity contrast of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$3.2 \times 10^6$$\end{document} for material at the surface versus material at the core-mantle-boundary temperature. Accordingly, a viscous upper thermal boundary layer (and comparatively rigid surface) can form within the regions intervening the weak bands formed by the strain-rate dependent yielding.

